<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12033c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12033c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12033c"> 33(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> fire out of heaven ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La dame acquies&ccedil;a d&apos;un air entendu. &ldquo;Donc, continuai-je, la premi&egrave;re cloche dont les Annales du Mont aient gard&eacute; le souvenir se nommait Rollon; elle sonnait d&eacute;j&agrave;, en 1048, pour rallier les vassaux de l&apos;abbaye, quand celle-ci &eacute;tait attaqu&eacute;e par les brigands de Bretagne. Au cours des si&egrave;cles, on lui donna des s&oelig;urs et, gr&acirc;ce &agrave; la g&eacute;n&eacute;rosit&eacute; des rois de France, des princes de l&apos;Eglise et des d&eacute;vots p&egrave;lerins, le carillon du Mont-Saint-Michel fut un des plus beaux du monde; malheureusement le feu du ciel d&eacute;truisit souvent la tour et les cloches fondaient dans le brasier. [The lady agreed knowingly. &ldquo; So, I continued, the first bell of which the Mont Annals have a record was named Rollon; she sounded already, in 1048, to rally the abbey&apos;s vassals, when it was attacked by Breton thieves. In the course of the centuries, she was given sisters and, thanks to the generosity of the kings of France, the princes of the Church and devout pilgrims, the Mont-Saint-Michel carillon was one of the best in the world; unfortunately the fire from the skies would destroy the tower and the bells were melted down. <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 216-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
